#html.elem("details", attrs: ("class": "portfolio-item", "id": "project-sublime-music"))[#html.elem("summary")[#html.elem("div", attrs: ("class": "company-logo"))[#html.elem("img", attrs: ("alt": "Sublime Music Logo", "src": "./images/sublime-music-logo.png"))]#html.elem("h3")[Sublime Music#html.elem("a", attrs: ("aria-label": "Permalink to Sublime Music", "class": "permalink", "href": "#project-sublime-music"))[]]#html.elem("span")[November 2018 - December 2024]#html.elem("p")[#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://github.com/sublime-music/sublime-music", "target": "_blank"))[GitHub]|#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://sublimemusic.app", "target": "_blank"))[Website]| GPLv3+]]#html.elem("div")[#html.elem("p")[Sublime Music is a native, GTK3#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "http://www.subsonic.org/pages/index.jsp", "target": "_blank"))[Subsonic],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://airsonic.github.io/", "target": "_blank"))[Airsonic],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://gitlab.com/robozman/revel", "target": "_blank"))[Revel],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://github.com/sentriz/gonic", "target": "_blank"))[Gonic],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://www.navidrome.org/", "target": "_blank"))[Navidrome], client for the Linux Desktop that is written in#html.elem("b")[Python]. Sublime Music allows users to connect to multiple Subsonic API-compliant servers, and browse and play music from those servers.]#html.elem("p")[Other features include being able to play music through Chromecast devices on the same LAN;#html.elem("i")[Offline Mode]and the ability to cache songs for offline listening; a DBus MPRIS interface integration for controlling Sublime Music via#html.elem("code")[playerctl],#html.elem("code")[i3status-rust], KDE Connect, and other DBus MPRIS clients; a sophisticated play queue; playlist management; and more.]#html.elem("p")[I began this project after migrating to Airsonic for music hosting because I was dissatisfied with the existing Airsonic clients on Linux.]#html.elem("p")[Sublime Music is developed on#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://github.com/sublime-music/sublime-music", "target": "_blank"))[GitHub]and is available via the#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://aur.archlinux.org/packages/sublime-music/", "target": "_blank"))[AUR],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://search.nixos.org/packages?show=sublime-music&query=sublime-music&channel=20.09", "target": "_blank"))[NixOS 20.09],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://packages.debian.org/bullseye/sublime-music", "target": "_blank"))[Debian Testing], and#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://pypi.org/project/sublime-music/", "target": "_blank"))[PyPi].]]]

#html.elem("details", attrs: ("class": "portfolio-item", "id": "project-visplay"))[#html.elem("summary")[#html.elem("div", attrs: ("class": "company-logo"))[#html.elem("img", attrs: ("alt": "Visplay Logo", "src": "./images/visplay-logo.png"))]#html.elem("h3")[Visplay#html.elem("a", attrs: ("aria-label": "Permalink to Visplay", "class": "permalink", "href": "#project-visplay"))[]]#html.elem("span")[February 2018 - May 2020]#html.elem("p")[#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://gitlab.com/ColoradoSchoolOfMines/visplay", "target": "_blank"))[GitLab]| GPLv3+]]#html.elem("div")[#html.elem("p")[Visplay is a Mines ACM project. It's goal is to create a digital signage system with a dynamic, hierarchical configuration system which can be used in a wide variety of hardware and infrastructure configurations.]#html.elem("p")[I worked on the initial design of the overall architecture of the project. I have also contributed in a project management role. I worked on the Python components of the project which consume the configuration files and generate playlists. I also led development of the web configuration frontend.]#html.elem("p")[Currently, I am working in an advisory role as an industry project mentor.]]]

#html.elem("details", attrs: ("class": "portfolio-item", "id": "project-mlocate"))[#html.elem("summary")[#html.elem("div", attrs: ("class": "company-logo"))[#html.elem("img", attrs: ("alt": "MLocate Logo", "class": "with-bg", "src": "./images/mlocate-logo.png"))]#html.elem("h3")[MLocate#html.elem("a", attrs: ("aria-label": "Permalink to MLocate", "class": "permalink", "href": "#project-mlocate"))[]]#html.elem("span")[February 2019]#html.elem("p")[Second Place |#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://gitlab.com/ColoradoSchoolOfMines/mlocate", "target": "_blank"))[GitLab]| AGPLv3+]]#html.elem("div")[#html.elem("p")[This project won#html.elem("em")[Second Place]at#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://hackcu.org/", "target": "_blank"))[HackCU V].]#html.elem("p")[Read my blog post about this hackathon:#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "<!--TWYLA-HUGO:ref \"/posts/hackathons/hackcu-v\"-->"))[HackCU V].]#html.elem("p")[MLocate is a comprehensive system for tracking and locating devices within an indoor space just using Wi-Fi ping signals. Using three specially configured Wi-Fi access points, we were able to capture signal strength from every device in the room by MAC address. Then, applying Radio Signal Strength Indication (RSSI) models, we were able to derive distance from signal strength which allowed us to use standard triangulation algorithms for determining the location of all of every device in the room.]#html.elem("p")[I worked on the triangulation logic for pinpointing device locations given distances calculated from signal strength. I also built the web frontend for displaying device locations.]#html.elem("p")[MLocate was a hackathon project by#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://www.bencarlson.dev/", "target": "_blank"))[Ben Perkins],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://gitlab.com/Jnunez101", "target": "_blank"))[Jesus Nuñez],#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://gitlab.com/nickjar99", "target": "_blank"))[Nick Jarmusz], (all freshmen) and myself. We developed it during a 24 hour period at the#html.elem("a", attrs: ("href": "https://hackcu.org/", "target": "_blank"))[HackCU]hackathon.]]]

